# Function to detect outliers using IQR method
def detect_outliers_iqr(df_copy, col):
    Q1 = df_copy[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df_copy[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = df_copy[(df_copy[col] < lower_bound) | (df_copy[col] > upper_bound)]
    return outliers

# Loop through each numerical column and check for outliers
for col in numeric_cols:
    outliers = detect_outliers_iqr(df_copy, col)
    if not outliers.empty:
        print(f"Outliers detected in {col}:")
        print(outliers[[col]])
    else:
        print(f"No outliers detected in {col}.")

# Function to fill missing values based on outliers check
def fill_missing_values(df_copy, col):
    outliers = detect_outliers_iqr(df_copy, col)
    if not outliers.empty:
        # If outliers are present, replace missing values with median
        df_copy[col].fillna(df_copy[col].median(), inplace=True)
    else:
        # If no outliers, replace missing values with mean
        df_copy[col].fillna(df_copy[col].mean(), inplace=True)

# Apply the function to fill missing values in each numerical column
for col in numeric_cols:
    fill_missing_values(df_copy, col)

# Create a DataFrame with the numerical features and their skewness
skew_df = pd.DataFrame(numeric_cols, columns=['Feature'])

# Calculate skewness for each numerical feature
skew_df['Skew'] = skew_df['Feature'].apply(lambda feature: scipy.stats.skew(df_copy[feature].dropna()))

# Calculate the absolute skewness
skew_df['Absolute Skew'] = skew_df['Skew'].apply(abs)

# Flag features that are skewed based on a threshold (e.g., skewness >= 0.6)
skew_df['Skewed'] = skew_df['Absolute Skew'].apply(lambda x: True if x >= 0.6 else False)

# Display the resulting DataFrame
print(skew_df)

from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

if (df_copy['LAT'] <= 0).any() or (df_copy['LON'] <= 0).any():
    # Shift the values to make them positive for log transformation
    df_copy['LAT'] = df_copy['LAT'] - df_copy['LAT'].min() + 1
    df_copy['LON'] = df_copy['LON'] - df_copy['LON'].min() + 1

# Apply log transformation to reduce skewness
df_copy['LAT_normalized'] = np.log(df_copy['LAT'])
df_copy['LON_normalized'] = np.log(df_copy['LON'])

# Scale the normalized data to bring values between 0 and 1
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
df_copy[['LAT_normalized', 'LON_normalized']] = scaler.fit_transform(df_copy[['LAT_normalized', 'LON_normalized']])

# Frequency Encoding for high-cardinality columns
high_cardinality_cols = ['LOCATION', 'Mocodes', 'Crm Cd Desc']
for col in high_cardinality_cols:
    freq_map = df_copy[col].value_counts(normalize=True)
    df_copy[col + '_encoded'] = df_copy[col].map(freq_map)

# One-Hot Encoding for low-cardinality, non-ordinal columns
one_hot_cols = ['AREA NAME', 'Vict Sex', 'Premis Desc', 'Weapon Desc']
df_copy = pd.get_dummies(df_copy, columns=one_hot_cols, drop_first=True)

# Label Encoding for ordinal columns
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

label_cols = ['Status', 'Status Desc', 'Vict Descent']
le = LabelEncoder()
for col in label_cols:
    df_copy[col + '_encoded'] = le.fit_transform(df_copy[col])

categorical_cols = high_cardinality_cols + one_hot_cols + label_cols
existing_cols = [col for col in categorical_cols if col in df_copy.columns]
df_copy = df_copy.drop(columns=existing_cols)

# Ensure date columns are in proper datetime format
df_copy['Date Rptd'] = pd.to_datetime(df_copy['Date Rptd'], errors='coerce')
df_copy['DATE OCC'] = pd.to_datetime(df_copy['DATE OCC'], errors='coerce')

# Extract Year, Month, Day, and Day of Week
df_copy['Rpt Year'] = df_copy['Date Rptd'].dt.year
df_copy['Rpt Month'] = df_copy['Date Rptd'].dt.month
df_copy['Rpt Day'] = df_copy['Date Rptd'].dt.day
df_copy['Rpt Day of Week'] = df_copy['Date Rptd'].dt.day_name()  # Day names like Monday, Tuesday

df_copy['Occ Year'] = df_copy['DATE OCC'].dt.year
df_copy['Occ Month'] = df_copy['DATE OCC'].dt.month
df_copy['Occ Day'] = df_copy['DATE OCC'].dt.day
df_copy['Occ Day of Week'] = df_copy['DATE OCC'].dt.day_name()  # Day names like Monday, Tuesday

# Indicator for Weekend (1 if the day is Saturday or Sunday, else 0)
df_copy['Rpt Weekend'] = df_copy['Rpt Day of Week'].isin(['Saturday', 'Sunday']).astype(int)
df_copy['Occ Weekend'] = df_copy['Occ Day of Week'].isin(['Saturday', 'Sunday']).astype(int)

# Calculate the delay in reporting (in days)
df_copy['Reporting Delay'] = (df_copy['Date Rptd'] - df_copy['DATE OCC']).dt.days

Advanced Analysis - Forecasting using ARIMA¶

In [65]:
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf, plot_pacf


df_copy['DATE OCC'] = pd.to_datetime(df_copy['DATE OCC'])

crime_time_series = df_copy.groupby('DATE OCC').size()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
crime_time_series.plot()
plt.title('Daily Crime Counts')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Crime Count')
plt.grid()
plt.show()

from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller

result = adfuller(crime_time_series)
print('ADF Statistic:', result[0])
print('p-value:', result[1])
if result[1] < 0.05:
    print("The time series is stationary.")
else:
    print("The time series is not stationary. Differencing is needed.")

crime_time_series_diff = crime_time_series.diff().dropna()

plot_acf(crime_time_series_diff, lags=20)
plot_pacf(crime_time_series_diff, lags=20)
plt.show()

model = ARIMA(crime_time_series, order=(1, 1, 1))  # (p, d, q)
arima_result = model.fit()

print(arima_result.summary())

forecast_steps = 30  # Forecast for the next 30 days
forecast = arima_result.get_forecast(steps=forecast_steps)
forecast_index = pd.date_range(start=crime_time_series.index[-1], periods=forecast_steps + 1, freq='D')[1:]
forecast_series = pd.Series(forecast.predicted_mean, index=forecast_index)
forecast_conf_int = forecast.conf_int()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(crime_time_series, label='Observed')
plt.plot(forecast_series, label='Forecast', color='red')
plt.fill_between(
    forecast_index, 
    forecast_conf_int.iloc[:, 0], 
    forecast_conf_int.iloc[:, 1], 
    color='pink', 
    alpha=0.3
)
plt.title('Crime Forecasting with ARIMA')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Crime Count')
plt.legend()
plt.grid()
plt.show()
